Sets of age - and sex specific rates represent refined measures of mortality, but they are cumbersome and difficult to assimilate. It is desirable, therefore to have a summary measure which epitomizes a whole set of rates but which avoids the crudity of the crude death rate. Demographers have used their technical skills to produce several measures and two of the most widely used will now be discussed to illustrate the procedure known as standardization. By this procedure, death rates are adjusted or standardized for the age and sex composition of the population. Standardization can be regarded as a means of holding age and sex constant.

