\section*{Age Misreporting}

Distortion in age distribution may be real and is caused by past changes in the levels or patterns of mortality, fertility or migration or they may be due to errors. The errors may be caused either by some individuals being incorrectly omitted from a survey or by ones individuals ages being wrongly reported.

A great problem for formal demography, frequently prohibiting the use of conventional techniques is that people simply do not tell the truth.

This is not a problem in developed countries but in many parts of the world, age misreporting can take two basic forms:-
- Age heaping
- Age shifting

\section*{Age Heaping}

Age heaping or digit preference as it is often called. Too many people report ages ending with 0 or 5 while relatively few people give ages ending in $9,1,4$ or 6 . For example, if in this group ones age is 22 , the individual will report this age as 20 years or 25 years.

\section*{Age Shifting}

Age shifting is a more serious problem than age heaping largely because it is harder to detect and adjust. Typically older people tend to exaggerate their ages, particularly where age confers status. Young men may underrate their age to avoid state free services. While older unmarried women may underrate their age.

Numerous techniques exist both to estimate the extent to which ages are misreported and to correct age distributions. Techniques for adjusting and smoothing ages are often complex and will not be discussed at this level. Whipple's index is a measure of preferences for ages ending in 0 and 5 . It takes ages between 23 and 62 because outside this range shifting and other problems always tend to confuse the normal pattern of heaping. The index is calculated simply by expressing the population reporting age ending with 0 and 5 as a percentage of the total population age between $23 \& 62$ and multiplying by 5 .

The range of the index is then from 100 indicating no preference for 0 and 5 up to 500 indicating that only 0 and 5 were reported.

